results.notes:
11-12 single mushrooms and one “triplet,” all growing out of pure mud, scattered in a compact area next to a path in a small grove next to a pond.

See also first observation dated 5/12/22 of two ‘baby’ versions of this mushroom, in the same grove.

Exterior of stem is rusty reddish brown with no veil, interior flesh is firm and bright white. Cap is flat to slightly convex, medium brown, dry and firm like a shiitake, not sticky or crumbly at all but almost soft/velvety feeling. Cap edges are beautifully ruffled, almost pleated.

Gills are subdecurrent (I think!), rusty reddish brown at the outside edges and otherwise white/beige when mature and fresh, turning rusty brown as the mushroom dries out. I cut the fresh gills with a sharp blade and there was no exudate.

There was a firm, compact ball of mycelia at the base of the one I dug up and replanted, but no volva. Some of the mushrooms had been nibbled on (slugs?) and broken so I could easily see the insides.
